                                                <p> <hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE.—<name type="person">Private Peter Chester</name>, <name type="organization">Co. K, 6th Maine
                                                  Volunteers</name>, aged 22 years, was wounded on <date type="injury" when="1863-11-07">November
                                                                  7th, 1863</date>, by a conoidal ball, which entered over
                                                  the fourth dorsal vertebra and fracturing its
                                                  spine passed upward toward the right shoulder, and
                                                  lodged. There was also a flesh wound of the middle
                                                  third of the left thigh. He was sent to
                                                                <name type="place" key="#Washington">Washington</name>, and, on <date type="admit" when="1863-11-09">November 9th</date>, was admitted
                                                                into the <name type="hospital" key="175">Stanton Hospital</name>. There was inflammatory
                                                  fever, with a quick pulse, and the wounds
                                                  suppurated freely. Simple dressings were applied;
                                                  anodynes and stimulants were administered, and a
                                                  full diet was allowed. On <date type="operation" when="1863-11-13">November 13th</date>, some
                                                  pieces of the spine of the vertebra were removed
                                                  from the wound. By November 19th, the patient was
                                                  free from pain, and the wound was healing. On
                                                                <date type="operation" when="1864-01-05">January 5th</date>, the ball was extracted from under the
                                                  edge of the trapezius muscle by counter incision.
                                                  The patient was returned to duty on <date type="duty" when="1864-04-24">April 24th,
                                                  1864</date>. He is a pensioner. <name type="person">Pension Examiner T. A.
                                                                  Foster</name> reports, <date type="pension" when="1866-05-18">May 18th, 1866</date>, that there is loss
                                                  of power in arms. His disability is rated total and permanent. </p>
                                                
